<subSubSection lastPageId="76" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1436,1529,2022]" lastBlockId="76.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="76" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1997,2022]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Comments.</emphasis>
The length of spicules in our material exceeds that of all specimens previously studied in 
<collectingCountry box="[1365,1436,1997,2022]" name="Belize" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Belize</collectingCountry>
and elsewhere in the Caribbean (
<bibRefCitation author="Parra-Velandia" box="[534,850,151,176]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" refString="Parra-Velandia, F. J., Zea, S. &amp; van Soest, R. W. M. (2014) Reef sponges of the genus Agelas (Porifera: Demospongiae) from the Caribbean Sea. Zootaxa, 3794 (3), 301 - 343. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3794.3.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Parra-Velandia 
<emphasis box="[712,779,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">et al.,</emphasis>
<number box="[789,850,152,176]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Unlike these authors, we find acanthostyles with reduced spines along the middle of the shaft, a characteristic thought to be unique to 
<taxonomicName authority="Wilson, 1902" authorityName="Wilson" authorityYear="1902" class="Demospongiae" family="Agelasidae" genus="Agelas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="schmidti">
<emphasis box="[1148,1330,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Agelas schmidti</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" refString="Wilson, H. V. (1902) The sponges collected in Porto Rico in 1899 by the U. S. Fish Commission Steamer Fish Hawk. Bulletin of the United States Fish Commission, 2, 375 - 411." type="journal article" year="1902">
Wilson, 
<number box="[151,208,224,248]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" value="1902.0">1902</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[269,391,224,248]" class="Demospongiae" family="Agelasidae" genus="Agelas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="sventres">
<emphasis box="[269,391,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">A. sventres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lehnert &amp; van 
<bibRefCitation author="Soest" box="[575,707,223,248]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" refString="Lehnert, H. &amp; van Soest, R. W. M. (1996) North Jamaican deep forereef sponges. Beaufortia, 46 (4), 53 - 81." type="journal article" year="1996">
Soest, 
<number box="[650,707,223,248]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) (see below). However, examining illustrations and specimens of other, not yellow-orange species, for instance, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmidt, 1870) (Wiedenmayer, 1977)" authorityName="(Schmidt, 1870) (Wiedenmayer" authorityYear="1977" box="[695,1332,260,285]" class="Demospongiae" family="Agelasidae" genus="Agelas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="conifera">
<emphasis box="[695,875,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Agelas conifera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt" box="[894,1064,260,285]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" refString="Schmidt, O. (1870) Grundzuge einer Spongien-Fauna des atlantischen Gebietes. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, iii - iv, 1 - 88, pls. I - VI." type="book chapter" year="1870">
Schmidt, 
<number box="[1006,1064,260,284]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" value="1870.0">1870</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Wiedenmayer" box="[1090,1324,260,285]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" refString="Wiedenmayer, F. (1977) Shallow-water sponges of the western Bahamas. Experimentia Supplementum 28, Birkhauser Verlag, Basel &amp; Stuttgart, pp. 1 - 287, pls. 1 - 43." type="journal article" year="1977">
Wiedenmayer, 
<number box="[1264,1324,260,284]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" value="1977.0">1977</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, we find similar spine reductions. This raises the possibilities that the morphological aberration is age- or environmentrelated and not a useful taxonomic feature.
</paragraph>
